Title: Security Awareness Training Evidence

Purpose
To demonstrate that all personnel complete regular security awareness training and understand their responsibilities.

Process

All employees and long‑term contractors must complete baseline security training within 30 days of hire and annually thereafter.

Content covers phishing, password/SSO usage, data classification, incident reporting, and acceptable use.

A central system (LMS, HRIS, or spreadsheet) tracks: name, role, hire date, last training date, and quiz score if applicable.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Training completion reports (CSV/PDF export) for the audit period.

Sample quiz results or certificates.

A list of overdue users and remediation actions, if any.

10.3 Vulnerability Scan Reports
Title: Vulnerability Management Evidence

Purpose
To show regular vulnerability scanning of in‑scope assets and tracking of remediation.

Process

Scope: Production infrastructure (hosts, containers), Internet‑facing endpoints, and key corporate assets (VPN, IdP, etc.).

Frequency: At least monthly for external scans; at least quarterly for internal/application scans.

Steps:

Run scheduled scans using <tool>.

Triage findings; assign severity (Critical/High/Medium/Low).

Create tickets for remediation of Critical/High issues.

Track remediation to closure and verify via re‑scan.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Monthly scan reports or dashboards.

Sample remediation tickets with links to specific findings.

Before/after scans showing reduced risk where appropriate.

10.4 Penetration Test Reports
Title: Penetration Testing Evidence

Purpose
To validate that external assessments of Kahana’s security posture are conducted and acted upon.

Process

Frequency: At least annually, and after major architectural changes.

Scope: Internet‑facing application and APIs; optionally internal components.

An independent third party performs testing based on an agreed scope and methodology.

Findings are triaged, and remediation tasks are logged and tracked to closure.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Latest pen test report (sanitized if necessary).

Remediation plan and tickets for High/Critical issues.

Confirmation of retesting for fixed issues.

10.5 Change Management Tickets
Title: Change Management Evidence

Purpose
To demonstrate that production changes are controlled, approved, and documented.

Process

Scope: All changes to production application code, infrastructure, and security configurations.

Each change must have a ticket including: description, risk/impact, rollback plan, reviewer, and approver.

Changes are tested in staging where feasible before production deployment.

Emergency changes are documented retrospectively with justification.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Population of change tickets across the period.

Samples showing approvals, testing notes, and rollout dates.

CI/CD release logs linked to tickets, where available.

10.6 Incident Response Records
Title: Incident Management Evidence

Purpose
To show that security incidents are identified, investigated, and resolved according to the IR plan.

Process

All suspected security incidents must be logged in <tool> and triaged by the Security Lead or delegate.

Each incident record includes: date/time, reporter, systems/users affected, severity, timeline of actions, and resolution.

Post‑incident reviews are conducted for significant incidents to capture lessons learned and prevention measures.

Evidence kept for Type II:

List of incidents (including “no major incidents” if true).

Detailed records for each incident in the period.

Post‑mortems / lessons learned documents.

10.7 Backup Test Results
Title: Backup and Restore Testing Evidence

Purpose
To verify that critical data backups can be successfully restored.

Process

Scope: Production databases and any critical configuration/state stores.

Frequency: At least quarterly.

Test types: Point‑in‑time restore to a non‑production environment, or file/object restore tests as appropriate.

Each test is documented with: date, system, backup source, restore target, success/failure, and issues.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Test run logs or screenshots.

Short test reports summarizing results and fixes.

Tickets for any issues found and their resolution.

10.8 System Monitoring Logs
Title: Monitoring and Logging Evidence

Purpose
To show that systems are monitored and logs are collected, retained, and reviewed.

Process

Application and infrastructure logs are centralized into <platform> (e.g., CloudWatch, Datadog, ELK).

Alerts are configured for key conditions: errors, performance degradation, security events, and availability issues.

On‑call engineers and/or security staff respond to alerts and document actions in tickets.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Screenshot or export of key dashboards.

Examples of alert notifications and associated tickets.

Log samples demonstrating retention for the required period.

10.9 Vendor Review Documentation
Title: Vendor Risk Management Evidence

Purpose
To demonstrate that third‑party vendors are assessed and monitored.

Process

All new vendors handling customer or internal confidential data must undergo a security review before onboarding.

For critical vendors, Kahana collects and reviews SOC 2 reports, security documentation, or questionnaires at least annually.

Risks, exceptions, and mitigations are documented and approved by the Security Lead or delegate.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Completed vendor questionnaires or review checklists.

Copies/summaries of SOC reports and security addenda.

Records of yearly re‑assessments and decisions.

10.10 Business Continuity Test Results
Title: Business Continuity and DR Testing Evidence

Purpose
To show that BC/DR plans are exercised and improved.

Process

At least annually, Kahana runs a BC/DR exercise (tabletop or live failover) focusing on critical services and teams.

Each test has clear objectives, scope, participants, and scenarios.

Outcomes, gaps, and follow‑up actions are documented in a test report.

Evidence kept for Type II:

BC/DR test report(s) from the period.

Tickets for follow‑up improvements.

Updated BC/DR plan if changes were made.

10.11 Employee Onboarding/Offboarding Records
Title: Joiner/Mover/Leaver Evidence

Purpose
To confirm that access is provisioned and revoked in a controlled, timely manner.

Process

HR notifies IT/Security of new hires, role changes, and terminations via <HRIS/ticketing>.

Standard access profiles are applied based on role, with least privilege.

Offboarding tasks (account disabling, device return, access revocation) are executed on or before termination date.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Sample tickets for hires/leavers during the period.

HR export of personnel changes.

Cross‑check showing accounts disabled in IdP and key systems.

10.12 Audit Logs (Application & Infrastructure)
Title: Audit Logging Evidence

Purpose
To show that security‑relevant events are logged and retained.

Process

Application logs capture authentication events, key administrative actions, and data‑sensitive operations where feasible.

Infrastructure logs capture OS logins, configuration changes, and network activity (e.g., security groups).

Logs are stored centrally with restricted access and retained for at least <X> months.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Configuration screenshots of logging setup.

Sample log entries for key events.

Proof of retention (show logs from early and late in the period).

10.13 Evidence Collection Templates
Title: Evidence Collection Templates

Purpose
To standardize how ongoing evidence is collected, labeled, and stored.

Approach

For each control family (access management, training, vulnerability management, etc.), Kahana maintains a simple template (spreadsheet or form) indicating: data source, frequency, owner, and file naming convention.

Evidence is stored in a central repository (e.g., “SOC2 Evidence – YYYY”) with consistent folder structure by control and period.

Templates are reviewed annually and updated as needed.

10.14 Control Testing Documentation
Title: Internal Control Testing Evidence

Purpose
To demonstrate periodic internal testing of key controls.

Process

Quarterly, Kahana selects a subset of controls (e.g., access reviews, backups, changes, incident management) for sample testing.

For each control, an internal tester pulls a sample of records and evaluates design and operating effectiveness.

Results are documented in a brief test report with findings and remediation actions.

Evidence kept for Type II:

Control test plans and sampling criteria.

Completed test worksheets.

Tickets raised for deficiencies and follow‑up reviews.

11. Supplementary Docs – Draft Descriptions
You mostly need short one‑paragraph descriptions in your SOC documentation index.

Service Level Agreements (SLAs)
Document outlines uptime and support commitments (e.g., target availability, response/resolution times, maintenance windows) for Kahana services and is shared with customers as part of contracts or product documentation.

Customer Data Processing Agreements (DPA)
Legal document describing how Kahana processes customer personal data, including roles (controller/processor), subprocessors, security measures, and data subject rights.

Insurance Certificates
Certificates of coverage for cyber liability and errors & omissions, maintained by Finance/Legal and updated upon policy renewal.

Office Lease/Physical Location Documentation
Lease and site description for the Chandigarh office, including building access controls, guards/reception policies, and any on‑site physical security measures.

Internal Audit Reports
Periodic self‑assessments or formal internal audit reports that evaluate SOC 2 controls, identify gaps, and track remediation.

12. Additional Policies – Draft One‑Paragraph Intros
You already have these mostly conceptually; you just need a short “what this policy covers” statement.

Network Security Policy
Defines how Kahana designs, secures, and monitors its networks, including segmentation, firewall configuration and review, VPN requirements for remote access, and restrictions on exposing services to the Internet.

Configuration Management Policy
Establishes requirements for baseline configurations, hardening standards, configuration changes (including approvals and testing), use of infrastructure‑as‑code, and detection/remediation of configuration drift.

Acceptable Use Policy (AUP)
Describes how employees, contractors, and other users may use Kahana systems and data, including prohibited activities, monitoring statements, device security requirements, and consequences for violations.

Risk Assessment Methodology
Documents how Kahana identifies assets, threats, vulnerabilities, and business impacts, and how it rates risks (likelihood/impact) and selects treatments, including review frequency and ownership.

Phishing Simulation Program
Describes the program for running periodic phishing simulations, measuring click/report rates, and providing targeted follow‑up training to improve user awareness.

